# Milestone 01 — From Broken Code to Healthy Containers

**Scope:** Stages 1–3 of the production-readiness project
(System Understanding → Debugging & Fixes → Containerization)

**Status at this milestone:** All four services (frontend, api, worker, redis) running as containers on a shared Docker network, all reporting `(healthy)`, with a job successfully flowing end-to-end: browser → frontend → API → Redis queue → worker → Redis status → API → browser.

---

## 1. What the system is

A job-processing pipeline of four services:

| Service  | Tech            | Role                                            | Listens on |
|----------|-----------------|--------------------------------------------------|------------|
| frontend | Node.js/Express | Serves the UI, forwards requests to the API      | 3000       |
| api      | Python/FastAPI  | Creates jobs, writes status, answers status queries | 8000    |
| redis    | Redis 7         | Job queue (list) + status board (hashes)         | 6379       |
| worker   | Python          | Pulls jobs from the queue, processes, marks complete | — (no port) |

Key architectural fact: the API and worker never talk to each other directly — only through Redis. This decoupling is what allows scaling workers independently later.

Core data-flow rule learned: **a port belongs to the one who listens.** Outgoing connections need no port declaration. The worker exposes nothing because nobody ever connects *to* it.

